DesignerPart.name: Ball
DesignerPart.description: Just a simple ball.

DesignerPart.name: Beacon Light
DesignerPart.description: Small blinking lights.

DesignerPart.name: Block
DesignerPart.description: Just a simple block.

DesignerPart.name: Camera
DesignerPart.description: Attach to your craft to add new views that you can cycle through during flight.

DesignerPart.name: Cargo Bay
DesignerPart.description: Cargo bay that can hold stuff and comes with two hinged doors by default.

DesignerPart.name: Small Bay
DesignerPart.description: Cargo bay that can hold stuff and comes with a single sliding door by default.

DesignerPart.name: Command Chip
DesignerPart.description: Compact and lightweight alternative to using a Space Capsule for controlling a craft.

DesignerPart.name: Command Disc
DesignerPart.description: A pack combining a command chip and space to have some batteries and gyroscopes to have all you need to control your craft in a single, more configurable part.

DesignerPart.name: Command Pod
DesignerPart.description: Controls the craft. Every rocket must have at least one command pod. This command pod has a built-in gyroscope for attitude control. Batteries are included.

DesignerPart.name: Komodo Command Pod
DesignerPart.description: Space capsule which includes a small amount of fuel and built-in engines.

DesignerPart.name: Patriot Capsule
DesignerPart.description: Space capsule that has a bit more leg room than the alternatives. Great capsule if you love your country and if you have the money.

DesignerPart.name: Space Capsule
DesignerPart.description: Controls the craft. Every rocket must have at least one capsule or command chip. Includes built-in gyroscope for attitude control. Batteries are included.

DesignerPart.name: Vroz Space Capsule
DesignerPart.description: Controls the craft. Every rocket must have at least one capsule or command chip. This capsule has a built-in gyroscope for attitude control. Batteries are included.

DesignerPart.name: Vroz Orbital Module
DesignerPart.description: Spherical space capsulse that fits quite nicely on top of the Vroz Descent Module in case you want to bring more people into space.

DesignerPart.name: Space Habitat
DesignerPart.description: A fuselage capable of holding crew inside, but with a very low density. Ideal for large vehicles such as spaceships, space stations and the like.

DesignerPart.name: Crew Compartment
DesignerPart.description: A fuselage capable of holding crew inside with a high density of seats, but with a limited pressure range to work. If under too much or too little pressure, it will take damage.

DesignerPart.name: Interstage
DesignerPart.description: Use this to split your craft into stages.

DesignerPart.name: Side Interstage
DesignerPart.description: Interstage that is designed to connect to the side of a fuel tank, but can connect to other places, too.

DesignerPart.name: Docking Port
DesignerPart.description: Allows connecting two crafts in flight so they can be friends and transfer fuel.

DesignerPart.name: Electric Motor (old)
DesignerPart.description: Motor that can continuously rotate parts. Uses Electricity.

DesignerPart.name: Electric Motor
DesignerPart.description: Motor that can continuously rotate parts. Uses Electricity.

DesignerPart.name: Mage I Engine
DesignerPart.description: Powerful engine that can be used for takeoff and orbiting. Not a great choice for landing on moons.

DesignerPart.name: Pixie I Engine
DesignerPart.description: Lower power engine useful for second stages and landing on small planetary bodies.

DesignerPart.name: Apex I Engine
DesignerPart.description: It's heavy, expensive, and drinks RP-1 like there's no tomorrow, but it will have the power to get even your most poorly engineered contraptions into space.

DesignerPart.name: Tourist
DesignerPart.description: They pay money to go places, but sadly they lack jetpacks and grappling hooks, how useless...

DesignerPart.name: Drood
DesignerPart.description: A mysterious being that resembles an Earthling. They can be a bit fragile but are great at exploring and piloting. You can put them into cockpits, cabins or seats to control your crafts even when out of power, and get them out in flight to have a walk.

DesignerPart.name: Chair
DesignerPart.description: Astronauts will stand as long as you ask them to, but sometimes it's nice to give them a break and let them sit down.

DesignerPart.name: Fairing
DesignerPart.description: Protects precious cargo on its way to space.

DesignerPart.name: Fairing Base
DesignerPart.description: The base of your fairings. When using fairings, this must be the first part you connect to your craft.

DesignerPart.name: Fairing Nose Cone
DesignerPart.description: Nose cone specially designed to only connect to fairings.

DesignerPart.name: Fin
DesignerPart.description: Smaller wing section designed for rockets.

DesignerPart.name: Fuel Adapter
DesignerPart.description: Makes it easier to connect engines to odd places on fuel tanks.

DesignerPart.name: Fuel Tank
DesignerPart.description: Versatile fuel tank that can be resized into many shapes and can hold many different types of fuel.

DesignerPart.name: Fuel Cell
DesignerPart.description: A generator capable of turning fuel into power. It is far from efficient burning it, but it can be a lighter and more compact alternative to large batteries.

DesignerPart.name: RTG
DesignerPart.description: Radioisotope Thermal Generators can be treated as a passive source of power thanks to their insanely radioactive plutonium core. With this you can have power anywhere in the system, but it doesn't come for cheap.

DesignerPart.name: Gyroscope
DesignerPart.description: Allows attitude control without thrust. Uses electricity.

DesignerPart.name: Heat Shield
DesignerPart.description: Provides protection from intense heat during re-entry.

DesignerPart.name: Hinge Rotator
DesignerPart.description: Small motor that can rotate parts around a hinge.

DesignerPart.name: Inlet
DesignerPart.description: Inlets suck in air for jet engines. Make sure the front of the inlet isn't blocked by other parts, because that can obstruct its airflow.

DesignerPart.name: Ion Engine
DesignerPart.description: Extremely low power, high-efficiency engine that expels ions at nearly 50km/s. Requires electricity.

DesignerPart.name: Pegasus Engine
DesignerPart.description: High-bypass jet engines are the most fuel efficient style of jet engines, and are more commonly found on passenger airplanes where money matters.

DesignerPart.name: Griffin Engine
DesignerPart.description: This is a low-bypass jet engine that trades fuel efficiency for more thrust. It also includes an afterburner, which significantly increases its thrust and also makes it totally rad.

DesignerPart.name: Minotaur Engine
DesignerPart.description: With a great balance between power and efficiency, mid-bypass turbofans are the perfect election for mid size planes and small and fancy private jets.

DesignerPart.name: Centaur Engine
DesignerPart.description: Turbojets are the oldest and most inefficient of the jet engines. These were designed before engineers knew that redirecting some of the air around the core was more fuel efficient and produced more thrust.

DesignerPart.name: Label
DesignerPart.description: Displays text. For labeling stuff, or whatever.

DesignerPart.name: Airplane Landing Gear
DesignerPart.description: Customizable landing gear.

DesignerPart.name: Small Landing Gear
DesignerPart.description: Customizable landing gear.

DesignerPart.name: Landing Leg
DesignerPart.description: Useful for landing without smashing your engine into the ground.

DesignerPart.name: Merlin Leg
DesignerPart.description: A sturdy set of legs useful for landing without smashing your engines into the ground, with great aero for how far they can deploy

DesignerPart.name: KIS Leg
DesignerPart.description: A very advanced and modern landing leg that will allow you to bring down the rockets of the future

DesignerPart.name: Piston Leg
DesignerPart.description: A small and simple landing leg, capable of slowing down the impact on moon landers

DesignerPart.name: Light
DesignerPart.description: Use these to help light your way.

DesignerPart.name: Multi-function Display
DesignerPart.description: Runs special Vizzy programs to display interactive widgets during flight.

DesignerPart.name: Nose Cone
DesignerPart.description: When used correctly, nose cones can reduce drag.

DesignerPart.name: Hemisphere
DesignerPart.description: Half a sphere. Two of these make a ball. Don't expect them to roll nice though, the collider is just a cone, sadly.

DesignerPart.name: Parachute
DesignerPart.description: With this you should hopefully touch down with a more gentle touch, but don't push them too far or they will break.

DesignerPart.name: Drogue Chute
DesignerPart.description: Activate these in an atmosphere to reduce your chances of rapid unplanned disassembly.

DesignerPart.name: Piston
DesignerPart.description: Push parts away from each other with a customizable hydraulic piston.

DesignerPart.name: Skyline Prop
DesignerPart.description: Your classic civilian small aircraft propeller, suited for the early crafts that require of well rounded performance for cheap.

DesignerPart.name: RCS Nozzle
DesignerPart.description: Reaction control nozzles help provide precise attitude control. Uses monopropellant.

DesignerPart.name: Multi Directional RCS
DesignerPart.description: Reaction control nozzle that can gimbal and provide far greater control than a standard RCS nozzle. Some say it can do the work of five normal RCS nozzles.

DesignerPart.name: Spirit Engine
DesignerPart.description: This engine is not about power, but about precision. Capable of small orbit and attitude adjustments, this engine is a must in any deep space mission.

DesignerPart.name: Gnome Engine
DesignerPart.description: As close as a deflating balloon you can get in terms of complexity, but also in terms of thrust.

DesignerPart.name: Pixie Engine
DesignerPart.description: Low power engine useful for second stages and landing on small planetary bodies. Its electric pump allows for a quick start and very low throttling, but it requires to have some batteries on-board.

DesignerPart.name: Dragon Engine
DesignerPart.description: Highly efficient nuclear thermal engine. Warning: Do not lick.

DesignerPart.name: Mage Engine
DesignerPart.description: Powerful engine that can be used for takeoff and orbiting. Not a great choice for landing on moons.

DesignerPart.name: Wyvern Engine
DesignerPart.description: A sophisticated methalox engine with great efficiency thanks to one of the most advanced pump systems ever seen.

DesignerPart.name: Titan Engine
DesignerPart.description: Powerful and efficient engine that uses hydrolox and staged combustion.

DesignerPart.name: Apex Engine
DesignerPart.description: It's heavy, expensive, and drinks RP-1 like there's no tomorrow, but it will have the power to get even your most poorly engineered contraptions into space.

DesignerPart.name: Goblin Solid Motor
DesignerPart.description: Sugar, spice and everything nice. The favourite toy of any rocket nerd.

DesignerPart.name: Ifrit Solid Booster
DesignerPart.description: Powerful and cheap, but inefficient. Cannot be shut down once ignited.

DesignerPart.name: Phoenix Solid Booster
DesignerPart.description: An extremely powerful solid rocket motor. Brute forces its usefulness through sheer power with no concern for efficiency whatsoever.

DesignerPart.name: Rotator
DesignerPart.description: Small motor that can rotate parts.

DesignerPart.name: Car Wheel
DesignerPart.description: Resizable wheels that have a built-in electric motor.

DesignerPart.name: Offroad Wheel
DesignerPart.description: Resizable wheels that have a built-in electric motor.

DesignerPart.name: Shock
DesignerPart.description: Shocks are useful when you want to soften impact with terra firma.

DesignerPart.name: Solar Panel
DesignerPart.description: Single, stationary solar panel that can be resized.

DesignerPart.name: Solar Panel Array
DesignerPart.description: Configurable solar panel array that stows away into a remarkably small space.

DesignerPart.name: Structural Panel
DesignerPart.description: It may look like a wing, but it has no wing physics simulation. These are good when you need a lot of wing like shapes, but don't care if they generate lift. They don't take as much processing power as a normal wing, so your design will run a little faster.

DesignerPart.name: Strut
DesignerPart.description: Resizable strut that can help bolster your crafts.

DesignerPart.name: Test Dummy
DesignerPart.description: Human like device that can be used to monitor the safety of your crafts.

DesignerPart.name: Toggle Switch
DesignerPart.description: Switches when toggled.

DesignerPart.name: Wing
DesignerPart.description: Large wing section designed with airplanes in mind.
